76561198114528559,Not Recommended,263860,13178157,"Posted: 1 December, 2014",all,Flap,"I really want to love this game ! And if I manage to play a few multiplayer games, I might be able to like it. I love how it looks simple, how it allows to play a multiplayer strategic game in less than an hou, how it allows the player to take its time. I do also really like the look of the game and its mecanism :Few units with very distinct roles, feed lines that can be hijacked, simple fog of war and combat sytem giving its full value to scouting and sentries, simple but efficient planet upgrades, highest speed in systems you control... Really, that's plenty of clever and well thought minimalist mecanism.However, when the developers states ""Heavily focused at multiplayer"", it does not mean that multiplayer is particularly weel done. Actually, many features are missing to correctly organise games and interract with your oponents.No what it means, is that simple player, and more specifically the AI, is a joke.First, the AI does not follow the same rules as the player : ships are produced at their headquarter. The ennemy does not even try to develop its economy, nor properly attack you. It knows how to produce ships in its factories, but rarely does so. While conquering an HQ, I noticed that it was filled with siege and invasion ships : enough to wipe out half of the map, and conquere the rest. But none of these ships had ever moved from there. Worse : the ennemy did not seem to have produced any fighter, which could have helped him, against my strike.So, it really feels like the dev did not even try to implement any kind of AI, or that if they tried to do so, countless bugs severely crippled it down.""Missions"" might be more interresting, but they play like tower defense.So my only hope to fully appreciate this game would be a proper AI update, a more efficient way to organize multiplayer games (taking in account player scarcity), or be lucky enough to have someone logging at the same time as me...There is some great potential there. But the game needs more love !Should I recommand it ? Well, if you are ready to wait for someone and play multiplayer yes. Otherwise, no. Or hopefully, not yet..."
,Recommended,263860,21066232,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,LeoTindall,"TL;DR: Not flashy, not tactical; pure and unadulterated grand strategy with a beautiful atmosphere and deep, satisfying mechanics. Easily worth twice the price.This game is everything I've wanted in space grand strategy since I played Empire at War at age 10. The atmosphere, conveyed by the cleverly-animated background, the consistent and beautiful UI style, and the brilliant but subtle music, is reminiscent of DEFCON: Everybody Dies. While the game might appear simplistic and shallow on the surface, the variety and quality of the maps and a well-thought-out, perfectly balanced array of game mechanics makes it infinitely re-playable, especially with friends.A must for:anyone who wanted to be Ender, who likes DEF CON, or who thinks that the Galactic Map was the best part of Star Wars: Empire at War. This game is effectively the same as playing SWEaW in Galactic Map and always using autoresolve (but, of course, much better balanced for that purpose).Avoid it if:you preferred Call of Duty: Modern Warfare to Supreme Commander in 2007, or if what you most appreciate most in Total War games is watching the little men fight."
76561197980388104,Recommended,263860,12398747,"Posted: 7 October, 2014",all,Fluid,"The game is a solid concept. The mechanics are simple to learn and there are many different play-styles to try. A basic 'command and conquer' (the style, not the old title) strategy game which oozes with potential if the developers would give it a little more attention (a few mechanics are not explained fully, there are more things that could be added) and promotion (very few people I have come across, who would buy and play this game, know about it).If you love good, pure strategy games this WOULD be the one for you... IF it actually had an active community. I recommend the game highly, it's is very enjoyable and has ample replayability... if only if there were actually players to play against (AI get's predictable, like all games). I live in hope that someday this will be more popular."
,Recommended,263860,12270359,"Posted: 27 September, 2014",all,St0nkingByte,"An awesome take on a well established genreSPACECOMis a really neat game that takes on the well established 4X genre, boils it down to its most simple elements and presents it in a very approachable and playable fashion.  Somewhat akin to chess this doesn't ultimately make the game any less complex or deep because beneath the simple surface lies a hard-core strategy game that provides some amazing experiences.  Adding to the experience is the dichotomy that this game is both fast and slow.  What I mean is that you can play out a full battle in just 20 minutes, though most scenarios are longer, but in each session you can change strategies and try a different approach multiple times.  Bad decisions are not always fatal and often you can flip your entire approach around and claim victory from what you thought would have been defeat.  As you play you begin to see this shifts in strategy as mega strategies in themselves.OverallSPACECOMputs hard-core 4X strategy in a neat and simple to learn multiplayer package.  It's the kind of game where even when you lose you are usually having fun.  And isn't that the point of any game?One note, the single player experience is pretty simple and the AI fairly easy to defeat.  The real action is in multiplayer.  However with a small community around this game expect to open a game room and wait a bit before someone joins.  That said, your patience is almost always rewarded."
